coredata.dc:description:
This study introduces a straightforward and eco-friendly method for synthesizing carbon dots (CDs) by utilizing extracts from onion and lemon juice with simple microwave assistance. These CDs were subsequently incorporated into LaSrAl3O7:xSm3+ (x = 0.5, 1, 3, 5, 7, 9 mol %) (LSAO:xSm3+) nanoparticles (NPs) to form CDs@LSAO:Sm3+ nanocomposites (NCs) through an ultrasonication process. DRS measurements indicated a bandgap variation from 4.502 eV for the undoped LSAO to 4.287 eV for LSAO doped with 9 mol % Sm3+. Photoluminescence (PL) studies revealed that the integration of CDs into the LSAO:5Sm3+ matrix led to an 82.39-fold enhancement in PL intensity, a phenomenon attributed to a Förster resonance energy transfer (FRET) mechanism. The CDs@LSAO:5Sm3+ NCs exhibited an impressive color purity of 99.8 % and an internal quantum efficiency (I

      QE
   ) of 87.49 %, highlighting their potential for high-performance lighting solutions. Temperature-dependent PL (TDPL) spectra, recorded over the range of 298–473 K, demonstrated excellent thermal stability by maintaining 94.3 % of the initial PL intensity at 423 K and exhibiting a broad activation energy of 0.31 eV. Optical thermometry studies further revealed a high relative sensitivity of 3.97 % K-1 at 298 K, underscoring the promise of CDs@LSAO:5Sm3+ NCs for advanced thermal sensing applications. Moreover, these NCs were successfully applied in the fabrication of bright orange-red light-emitting diodes (LEDs) and cool w-LEDs, thereby emphasizing their utility in solid-state lighting. In addition, the NCs were employed for latent fingerprints (LFPs) detection, including twin fingerprints (FPs) analyses of male twins, male-female twins and female twins, as well as poroscopic studies of right and left thumb impressions from a female donor. The detection and comparison of LFPs were further enhanced by an artificial intelligence (AI)-enabled MATLAB algorithm that determined similarity scores between twin FPs and LFPs across various substrates for the same individual. Collectively, these findings highlight the multifunctional nature of CDs@LSAO:5Sm3+ NCs, establishing them as promising candidates for both optoelectronic applications and advanced forensic investigations.

ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para:
This study introduces a straightforward and eco-friendly method for synthesizing carbon dots (CDs) by utilizing extracts from onion and lemon juice with simple microwave assistance. These CDs were subsequently incorporated into LaSrAl3O7:xSm3+ (x = 0.5, 1, 3, 5, 7, 9 mol %) (LSAO:xSm3+) nanoparticles (NPs) to form CDs@LSAO:Sm3+ nanocomposites (NCs) through an ultrasonication process. DRS measurements indicated a bandgap variation from 4.502 eV for the undoped LSAO to 4.287 eV for LSAO doped with 9 mol % Sm3+. Photoluminescence (PL) studies revealed that the integration of CDs into the LSAO:5Sm3+ matrix led to an 82.39-fold enhancement in PL intensity, a phenomenon attributed to a Förster resonance energy transfer (FRET) mechanism. The CDs@LSAO:5Sm3+ NCs exhibited an impressive color purity of 99.8 % and an internal quantum efficiency (I

                        QE
                     ) of 87.49 %, highlighting their potential for high-performance lighting solutions. Temperature-dependent PL (TDPL) spectra, recorded over the range of 298–473 K, demonstrated excellent thermal stability by maintaining 94.3 % of the initial PL intensity at 423 K and exhibiting a broad activation energy of 0.31 eV. Optical thermometry studies further revealed a high relative sensitivity of 3.97 % K-1 at 298 K, underscoring the promise of CDs@LSAO:5Sm3+ NCs for advanced thermal sensing applications. Moreover, these NCs were successfully applied in the fabrication of bright orange-red light-emitting diodes (LEDs) and cool w-LEDs, thereby emphasizing their utility in solid-state lighting. In addition, the NCs were employed for latent fingerprints (LFPs) detection, including twin fingerprints (FPs) analyses of male twins, male-female twins and female twins, as well as poroscopic studies of right and left thumb impressions from a female donor. The detection and comparison of LFPs were further enhanced by an artificial intelligence (AI)-enabled MATLAB algorithm that determined similarity scores between twin FPs and LFPs across various substrates for the same individual. Collectively, these findings highlight the multifunctional nature of CDs@LSAO:5Sm3+ NCs, establishing them as promising candidates for both optoelectronic applications and advanced forensic investigations.

ce:section.ce:para:
In this context, LS refers to the emission spectrum of the sample measured inside the integrating sphere, ER represents the excitation light spectrum recorded without the sample, and ES corresponds to the excitation light spectrum with the sample placed inside the integrating sphere (Fig. 5
                        a & b). Based on Eq. (27), the IQE of LSAO:5Sm3+ nanoparticles and CDs@LSAO:5Sm3+ nanocomposites is calculated to be 79.96 % and 87.49 %, which is notably higher than that of previously reported Sm3+ doped phosphors (Table 9
                        ) [66,78–82], highlighting the superior efficiency of the synthesized materials. The absorption efficiencies (ξₐᵦc) for LSAO:5Sm3+ and CDs@LSAO:5Sm3+ nanocomposites were determined to be 0.578 and 0.619, respectively, while the corresponding EQE were calculated as 46.2 % and 54.15 %. These results demonstrate the strong potential of these materials as efficient color converters for near-UV-pumped w-LEDs. Further improvements in synthesis and optimization techniques may lead to even higher quantum efficiencies.

FP patterns in twins have long attracted forensic interest because of their genetic similarities. Although FPs are unique to each individual, monozygotic (identical) twins often display remarkably similar ridge configurations, with only minor variations arising from environmental and developmental influences during fetal growth [95]. In our analysis, we examined the right thumb FPs of male twins, the left thumb FPs of male–female twins and the right thumb FPs of female twins using fluorescent CDs@LSAO:5Sm3+ NCs. Under UV light, these composites markedly enhanced the visibility of minutiae. For example, Fig. 9
                         shows that in male twins the extracted minutiae features such as the right whorl, cross-over, enclosure, bifurcation, short ridge, double bifurcation, dot and sweat pore occurred at identical positions on both prints. Similarly, in male–female twins (Fig. 10
                        ) the mirror-image features identified include the left loop, delta, bifurcation, island, eye, scar and sweat pore, while for female twins (Fig. 11
                        ) the right loop, bifurcation, short ridge, fragmented island and scars were consistently observed. The key observation is that all twin FPs share the same Level 1 features (e.g., right whorl in male twins, left loop with delta formation in male–female twins and right loop in female twins), indicating that the global ridge configuration is strongly inherited. However, the finer Level 2 and Level 3 features provide the subtle differences essential for forensic differentiation. These results underscore that while genetic factors largely determine overall FP structure, slight developmental variations ensure each print retains individual uniqueness highlighting the importance of high-resolution imaging and advanced minutiae analysis in distinguishing twin FPs for forensic investigations.
